A class in Java is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines the properties (attributes) and behaviors (methods) that the objects created from the class will have. Every class in Java is derived from the Object class, which is the superclass of all classes in Java.

A class is declared using the 'class' keyword followed by the class name, which conventionally starts with an uppercase letter. The body of the class contains the declaration of member variables (fields) and methods. 

For example, a class can be declared as follows:

```java
public class Student {
    private String name;
    private int age;
    private double gpa;

    public Student(String name, int age, double gpa) {
        this.name = name;
        this.age = age;
        this.gpa = gpa;
    }

    public void displayInfo() {
        System.out.println("Name: " + name + ", Age: " + age + ", GPA: " + gpa);
    }
}
``` 

In this example, the class `Student` has three member variables (`name`, `age`, and `gpa`) and a constructor to initialize these variables, along with a method `displayInfo` to display the student's information.

